  "prompt": "How many known viruses can infect humans?",
  "response": "As of my knowledge cutoff in October 2023, scientists have identified and characterized **over 200 viruses** that are known to infect humans. This number continues to grow as research advances and new viruses are discovered through improved diagnostic techniques and surveillance efforts.\n\n### **Key Points:**\n\n1. **Diverse Families:** These human-infecting viruses belong to various families, each with distinct characteristics. Major families include:\n   - **Coronaviridae:** Includes SARS-CoV-2 (responsible for COVID-19), SARS-CoV, and MERS-CoV.\n   - **Orthomyxoviridae:** Includes Influenza viruses.\n   - **Retroviridae:** Includes HIV (Human Immunodeficiency Virus).\n   - **Picornaviridae:** Includes Enteroviruses like Poliovirus and Rhinoviruses causing the common cold.\n   - **Herpesviridae:** Includes Herpes Simplex Virus, Varicella-Zoster Virus (chickenpox and shingles), and Epstein-Barr Virus.\n   - **Flaviviridae:** Includes Hepatitis C Virus, Dengue Virus, and Zika Virus.\n\n2. **Emerging and Re-emerging Viruses:**\n   - **Zoonotic Origin:** Many new or re-emerging viruses originate from animal hosts and jump to humans, as seen with SARS-CoV-2 from bats.\n   - **Mutation and Evolution:** Viruses like influenza and coronaviruses undergo frequent mutations, leading to new strains and variants.\n\n3. **Impact on Health:**\n   - **Range of Diseases:** Human-infecting viruses can cause a spectrum of diseases, from mild respiratory infections to severe illnesses like Ebola, HIV/AIDS, and COVID-19.\n   - **Global Health Threats:** Some viruses have pandemic potential, necessitating global surveillance and rapid response strategies.\n\n4. **Classification and Taxonomy:**\n   - The **International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)** is responsible for the classification and naming of viruses. Their ongoing research contributes to the understanding and categorization of new viral species.\n\n5. **Challenges in Counting:**\n   - **Undiscovered Viruses:** It's estimated that there are many more viruses capable of infecting humans that have yet to be discovered, especially those causing asymptomatic or mild infections.\n   - **Variability in Classification:** Different criteria and ongoing research can lead to reclassification, mergers, or splits of viral species, affecting the total count.\n\n### **Conclusion:**\n\nWhile over 200 human-infecting viruses have been identified, the total number is likely higher and continues to increase with ongoing scientific research. Advances in genomics, molecular biology, and global surveillance are essential for uncovering and understanding the full spectrum of viruses that can impact human health.\n\nFor the most up-to-date and detailed information, resources such as the [World Health Organization (WHO)](https://www.who.int/), the [Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)](https://www.cdc.gov/), and the [International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)](https://ictv.global/) can be consulted.",
